01_Deriving_Risk_Difference

Arthur M. Albuquerque

May 13, 2021

In this document, I will provide the rationale for the effect sizes used in our project.

First, I will load the data and calculate the log-odds ratio (OR) of the RECOVERY trial and its corresponding prior included in our analyses. Next, I will use these calculate the odds ratio and then derive the risk differences.

Odds ratio, then risk difference

Our ultimate goal in this project is to report posterior distributions of risk difference (RD) for each subgroup. We will eventually compile multiple studies in our analyses and each have their own baseline risk (BR). Notably, RD is intrinsically related to BR. Therefore, different studies with distinct RDs are not comparable between each other.

To overcome this limitation regarding RD, we have decided to use a fixed BR for each subgroup. We will use the BR in the respective control group from the RECOVERY trial.

Doi et al. stated that RD should be derived from the odds ratio (OR). Thus, in combination with a fixed BR we will calculate RDs from OR. Here is the formula provided by Doi et al., where \(R D\) is risk difference, \(B R\) is baseline risk from the control group (no-exposure) and \(O R\) is odds ratio.

$$

\[\begin{aligned} R D=\frac{B R * \left(B R-1\right)* \left(O R-1\right)}{B R*O R-B R+1} \end{aligned}\]

$$

recovery_not_using =
  escalc(
    # Outcome
    measure = "OR", # Log-odds ratio
    
    # Tocilizumab group
    ai = events_toci,
    n1i = total_toci,

    # Control group
    ci = events_control,
    n2i = total_control,
    
    data = d2 %>% filter(outcome == "mortality",
                         corticosteroids == 0,
                         trial == "RECOVERY"),

    slab = paste(trial)
  )

logOR_recovery_not_using = rma(yi, vi, data=recovery_not_using) 

forest(logOR_recovery_not_using)

Calculating risk difference

As mentioned before, we will use the formula provided by Doi et al. to calculate the risk difference (RD) from a fixed baseline risk (BR) and odds odds ratio (OR).

$$

\[\begin{aligned} R D=\frac{B R * \left(B R-1\right)* \left(O R-1\right)}{B R*O R-B R+1} \end{aligned}\]

$$

In the sections before, we calculated the log-odds ratio for the RECOVEY trial and prior distributions for each subgroup. Of note, log-odds ratio is normal distributed.

Now, we will draw 100,000 samples using the log-odds ratio mean and its standard error for the RECOVERY trial and prior distributions for each subgroup. Next, we will exponentiate these values to obtain the odds ratio.

### RECOVERY trial

set.seed = 123 # for reproducibility

n = 1e5

## Use of corticosteroids

### Not using

estimates_RECOVERY_not_using = 
  tibble(
    logOR = rnorm(n, # Sampling size
        logOR_recovery_not_using$beta, # Mean
        logOR_recovery_not_using$se # Standard error
        )
    ) %>% 
  mutate(OR = exp(logOR))

### Using

estimates_RECOVERY_using =

    logOR = rnorm(n, # Sampling size

  mutate(OR = exp(logOR))

# Formula from Doi et al., 2020

RD_fun = function(BR,OR)
  {
( BR*(BR-1)*(OR-1) ) / ( BR*OR - BR+1)
}
# Calculating the risk differences

#### RECOVERY

### Use of corticosteroids

## Not using

# Define baseline risk
BR_not_using = d2 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",
           corticosteroids == 0, # Not using
           outcome == "mortality") %>% 
      summarise(n = events_control/total_control) %>%
      pull()

estimates_RECOVERY_not_using = 
  estimates_RECOVERY_not_using %>% 
  # Apply formula from Doi et al., 2020
  mutate(RD = RD_fun(BR_not_using,
                     OR))

## Using

# Define baseline risk
BR_using = d2 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",
           corticosteroids == 1, # Using
           outcome == "mortality") %>% 
      summarise(n = events_control/total_control) %>%
      pull()

estimates_RECOVERY_using = 
  estimates_RECOVERY_using %>% 
  # Apply formula from Doi et al., 2020
  mutate(RD = RD_fun(BR_using,
                     OR))

### Respiratory support

## Simple oxygen

# Define baseline risk
BR_simple = d1 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",
           oxygen == "simple oxygen",
           outcome == "mortality") %>% 
      summarise(n = events_control/total_control) %>% 
      pull()

estimates_RECOVERY_simple = 
  estimates_RECOVERY_simple %>% 
  # Apply formula from Doi et al., 2020
  mutate(RD = RD_fun(BR_simple,
                     OR))

## Non-invasive

# Define baseline risk
BR_noninvasive = d1 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",
           oxygen == "non-invasive ventilation",
           outcome == "mortality") %>% 
      summarise(n = events_control/total_control) %>% 
      pull()

estimates_RECOVERY_noninvasive = 
  estimates_RECOVERY_noninvasive %>% 
  # Apply formula from Doi et al., 2020
  mutate(RD = RD_fun(BR_noninvasive,
                     OR))

## Invasive mechanical ventilation

# Define baseline risk
BR_invasive = d1 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",

      pull()

estimates_RECOVERY_invasive =

p1 = estimates_RECOVERY_not_using %>%
